## What happened

In **.NET 11**, **DSA was removed from macOS**. Calling `DSA.Create()` (and any DSA sign/verify operation) now **throws at runtime on macOS**. It still works on Windows and Linux.

## How to fix it

Since you need to **verify legacy DSA signatures**, you have two options:

### Option 1 — Platform-gate DSA verification (keep legacy support on Windows/Linux)

```csharp
if (OperatingSystem.IsMacOS())
    throw new PlatformNotSupportedException("DSA verification is not supported on macOS in .NET 11+.");

using var dsa = DSA.Create();
dsa.ImportParameters(legacyPublicKey);
bool valid = dsa.VerifyData(data, signature, HashAlgorithmName.SHA256);
```

### Option 2 — Migrate to a modern algorithm (recommended long-term)

Replace DSA with **ECDsa**, **RSA**, or **Ed25519**. This requires re-signing existing artifacts with the new key, so it's a larger change:

```csharp
using var ecdsa = ECDsa.Create();
var valid = ecdsa.VerifyData(data, signature, HashAlgorithmName.SHA256);
```

**Bottom line:** If you must continue verifying existing DSA signatures, restrict that code path to Windows/Linux. For new signatures, migrate to ECDSA or RSA.
